<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is an easement on a Brisbane property?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "An easement is a registered right for someone else to use part of your land for a specific purpose. Common examples on Brisbane residential properties include council drainage easements, service easements for water and sewerage mains, and access easements that allow neighbours or the council to cross your land. The easement is attached to the land title and transfers with the property when it is sold."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do I have to disclose easements and encumbrances when selling in Queensland?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. In Queensland, the contract of sale must accurately disclose title encumbrances including easements, covenants, and charges. A buyer's solicitor will conduct a title search and any undisclosed encumbrance discovered after contract can give the buyer grounds to terminate. Your solicitor prepares the contract and is responsible for ensuring the title is correctly described."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can I build over an easement on my Brisbane property?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Generally no, not without approval from the relevant authority. Most drainage, sewerage, and service easements on Brisbane residential titles prohibit permanent structures over them. Brisbane City Council will not approve building work over a stormwater drainage easement. Sewerage easements held by Urban Utilities similarly restrict building. The restrictions are enforced through the easement conditions registered on title."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>

<article style="background:var(--color-surface-0);min-height:100vh;">

