      </a>
      <span style="display:block;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.6rem;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#f5d07a;margin-bottom:1rem;">Buyers &amp; Sellers &middot; 6 min read</span>
      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Easements and Encumbrances on Your Brisbane Property
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        What they are, how they appear on title, what sellers must disclose, and what buyers are actually looking for when they order a title search.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most sellers encounter the words easement and encumbrance during the contract preparation stage, often for the first time, and find them unsettling. They shouldn't. These are standard registered interests that appear on a significant proportion of Brisbane residential titles and, in most cases, have no material effect on a sale. What matters is understanding what you have, disclosing it correctly, and being straightforward with buyers so nothing comes as a surprise after contracts are signed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What an easement actually is</h2>
      <p>An easement is a registered right for another party to use part of your land for a defined purpose. The easement is attached to the land title, not to you as the owner, which means it transfers automatically when the property is sold. You cannot remove an easement by selling the property.</p>

      <p>The party who benefits from the easement is called the dominant tenement. The land that carries the burden is called the servient tenement. In Brisbane, the most common easements on residential properties are:</p>

      <ul style="padding-left:1.5rem;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;">
        <li><strong>Drainage easements</strong> registered in favour of Brisbane City Council or the relevant local authority. These typically run along the rear or side of a lot and protect a stormwater or drainage infrastructure corridor. You cannot build a permanent structure over them without council approval, which is rarely granted.</li>
        <li><strong>Sewerage and water main easements</strong> registered in favour of Urban Utilities or Queensland Urban Utilities. These protect buried water and sewerage infrastructure. Similar building restrictions apply.</li>
        <li><strong>Access easements</strong> that give a neighbouring property the right to cross part of your land, usually to reach a public road. These are common on battleaxe blocks and properties with shared driveways.</li>
        <li><strong>Power line easements</strong> registered in favour of Energex, typically on larger lots or properties near high-voltage infrastructure.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Most of these easements are benign in practice. A drainage easement running along the back fence of a standard inner Brisbane lot affects very little usable land and has no impact on how the property is lived in, marketed, or sold. Buyers and their solicitors are accustomed to seeing them. The issue arises only when a seller has built over an easement without approval, or when the easement affects a significant portion of the usable land.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How easements are revealed and what they restrict</h2>
      <p>Easements are registered on the property's title and appear in a title search. They are also shown on the relevant survey plan, which identifies the physical location and dimensions of the easement corridor on the lot. Your solicitor will include this information in the contract of sale. A buyer's solicitor will order their own title search and examine it carefully.</p>

      <p>The practical restriction is straightforward: you cannot build a permanent structure over most easements without written approval from the benefiting authority. For drainage easements, that means no sheds, garages, pools, decking with footings, or extensions. For sewerage easements, Urban Utilities will not approve any structure that could impede access to the infrastructure beneath. Access easements must remain passable for the dominant tenement.</p>

      <p>Where problems arise is when a previous owner has already built over an easement. A pergola on footings sitting over a drainage easement, a garden shed anchored to a concrete slab over a sewerage line, or a pool that encroaches into an easement corridor are all situations that should be disclosed and, ideally, resolved before the property is listed. Council or the relevant utility authority can issue orders to remove unapproved structures over easements. Buyers who discover this after settlement have grounds for complaint.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What encumbrances are and how they differ from easements</h2>
      <p>Encumbrance is the broader term. An easement is one type of encumbrance, but the word also covers:</p>

      <ul style="padding-left:1.5rem;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;">
        <li><strong>Mortgages</strong>: a registered mortgage is an encumbrance. The lender holds a security interest over the property. At settlement, the proceeds are used to discharge the mortgage and the encumbrance is removed from title. This is the most common encumbrance on any residential property.</li>
        <li><strong>Statutory charges</strong>: unpaid council rates or water charges can result in a charge registered against the title. These must be cleared at settlement.</li>
        <li><strong>Covenants</strong>: a restrictive covenant is a registered obligation that limits what can be done with the land. Older estates in Brisbane's inner suburbs sometimes carry covenants restricting subdivision, mandating certain building materials, setting minimum setbacks, or specifying land use. They are registered on title and bind the owner regardless of when they purchased.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Covenants are worth particular attention because they can materially affect buyer plans. A buyer who intends to subdivide a lot or build a secondary dwelling may find that a registered covenant prevents it. Sellers are not required to investigate every buyer's intentions, but they are required to disclose covenants in the contract. A buyer who later discovers an undisclosed covenant that prevents them from implementing a development plan they communicated during negotiations has a legitimate complaint.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The seller's disclosure obligation</h2>
      <p>In Queensland, the Property Law Act 1974 and the standard REIQ contract require that the title be accurately described in the contract. Your solicitor prepares the contract and is responsible for ensuring that all registered interests, including easements, covenants, and charges, are correctly listed. You are not expected to be a conveyancing expert, but you should review the contract carefully before signing and confirm with your solicitor that everything on the title has been included.</p>

      <p>Where sellers sometimes create problems for themselves is by omitting interests they are aware of but assume are minor, or by failing to tell their solicitor about structures that may encroach on an easement. If a buyer discovers a material non-disclosure after signing, they may have the right to terminate the contract or claim compensation. The safe approach is full disclosure of everything and a clear conversation with your solicitor about anything you are uncertain about.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What buyers are looking for in a title search</h2>
      <p>A buyer's solicitor conducting a title search is looking for anything that affects the buyer's ability to use the property as they intend, or that creates a financial liability they would inherit. The key checks are:</p>

      <ul style="padding-left:1.5rem;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;">
        <li>Whether the property boundaries match what is being sold</li>
        <li>What easements exist and where they are located on the lot</li>
        <li>Whether any covenants restrict what can be done with the land</li>
        <li>Whether any registered charges or orders exist against the title</li>
        <li>Whether the existing mortgage will be discharged at settlement</li>
      </ul>

      <p>For most standard inner Brisbane residential sales, the title search is clean or contains only familiar items like a mortgage and a drainage easement. Buyers' solicitors see these regularly and do not raise them as concerns. The situations that create delays or negotiations are unapproved structures over easements, unexpected covenants, or charges that cannot be cleared at settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens to your mortgage at settlement</h2>
      <p>A registered mortgage is discharged at settlement from the sale proceeds. The process is handled electronically through PEXA, the national electronic settlement platform used by Queensland solicitors. Your lender is notified of the pending settlement, calculates the payout figure, and the relevant amount is transferred to them on settlement day. The mortgage is simultaneously removed from the title. You receive the net balance after the mortgage discharge, outstanding council and water adjustments, and any agreed deductions.</p>

      <p>The discharge of mortgage is not something sellers need to manage directly. Your solicitor coordinates with the lender. The only seller obligation is to ensure you have enough equity in the property to cover the payout figure, any costs, and still have a positive net. If the sale price is lower than your loan balance, you would need to make up the shortfall from other funds. This is unusual but worth understanding before you list.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Presenting title interests honestly to buyers</h2>
      <p>The most useful thing a seller can do is be straightforward about what is on the title and let buyers and their solicitors assess it properly. Trying to downplay or obscure a drainage easement or an old covenant rarely helps. Experienced buyers' solicitors will find it in the title search, and anything that appears to have been withheld creates a loss of trust that can complicate negotiations.</p>

      <p>Where an agent adds value is in explaining what a title interest means in practice, so that a buyer does not walk away from a perfectly solid property because they misread a drainage easement as a significant restriction. Most easements on Brisbane inner-east properties are along rear boundaries, affect a narrow strip of land, and have no bearing on how the property is used day to day. That context, delivered clearly before the buyer orders their own advice, keeps campaigns moving.</p>

      <div style="padding:1.5rem;background:rgba(245,208,122,0.06);border-left:3px solid #f5d07a;">
